<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>NORTH SEA HELICOPTER SAFETY</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Captain R Williams and Captain S Airey, Air Safety Group and PACTS </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(HCS0006)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Captain Williams is a former Chairman of the Air Safety Group (2006 – 2012), a wholly independent group of aviation professionals whose aim is to improve all aspects of aviation safety.  Captain Williams served as a professional Helicopter Pilot and spent </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">17 years operating offshore in British Airways Helicopters between 1965 and 1983.  During that time he served at various times as the company’s Air Safety Officer, Flight Technical Officer, Training Captain, Flight Simulator Manager (for the world’s first </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">civil helicopter simulator, the S61N helicopter) and Base Manager </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for the company’s first oversees offshore operation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in Germany)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.   He then became a Senior Manager for ten years (1987 – 1997) in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Safety Regulation Group of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK CAA as Head, Flight O</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">perations (Policy and Regulations).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Captain Steve Airey </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">read Aeronautical Engineering at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">University</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from 1981-1984. Joined the Royal Air Force and served as a helicopter pilot, including service in the Falkland Islands, the Gulf War, the Kurdis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">h Relief Operation and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Bosnia</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Deputy Flight Commander, Detachment Flight Commander, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Authoriser</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, Squadron Air-Test Pilot, Day and NVG (Night) Formation Leader. Airline Captain since 1997, firstly on the BAC 1-11 and then on the Airbus A319/320/321 at Heath</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">row. Became a Fellow of the Royal Aeronautical Society in 2011.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">THIS PAPER IS </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AIMED AT ADDRESSING THE MAIN QUESTION POSED BY THE TRANSPORT SELECT COMMITTEE CONCERNING “HOW SAFE ARE OFFSHORE HELICOPTER FLIGHTS?”</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As mentioned this submission is aimed solel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y at the first question posed.  This is simply because it has been some 30 years s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ince being intimately involved i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n North Sea helicopter operations and it is not therefore possible to address those additional questions relating to how the UK’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">current </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">safe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ty compares to other countries, what steps need to be taken to improve current safety standards, how legislation could be improved and how effective the Regulators </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in ensuring improvements are implemented.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  In summary</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, based upon the available statisti</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cs in terms of known fatal accidents/fatalities </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">over the 48 years of operations </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">estimated total number of flying hours an assessment can be made as follows: -</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">OVERALL, THE SAFETY OF </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> OFFSHORE HELICOPTER OPERATIONS, WHEN BASED OVER THE 48 YEARS S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">INCE IT COMMENCED, CAN BE </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ASSESSED AND </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DEEMED TO BE GOOD.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">THE CYCLICAL NATURE OF MAJOR INCIDENTS AND/OR ACCIDENTS DOES MEAN THAT OVER CERTAIN SHORT</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ER</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> PERIODS OF TIME, THE NUMBERS OF ACCIDENTS/FATALITIES DOES GIVE CAUSE FOR CONCERN </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(EVEN ONE IS ONE TOO MAN</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Y) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AND RIGHTLY CAUSES THE INDUSTRY TO BE REVIEWED WITH THE ONGOING AIM OF ENSURING</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> WHEREVER </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">IT IS </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">POSSIBLE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> THAT SAFETY IMPROVEMENTS ARE IMPLEMENTED.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">NORTH</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">SEA</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> HELICOPTER SAFETY</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Operating</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> helicopters in the unforgiving </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">North Sea</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> environment can be a potentially hazardous occupation that demands total concentration by all involved at al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l times.  It is now </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">some </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">48</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> years since the commencement of offshore helicopter operations, which began in 1965 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in the southern North Sea </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">when </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">search for gas </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">initially </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">began and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ying started out of North Denes airfield in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Great Yarmouth and Beccles </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">airfield </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">near </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Lowestoft</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">During that time there have been the inevitable major safety incidents and f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">atal </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">accidents.  Inevitable simply because w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">herever human beings are involved, mistakes and errors will always occur, either in the manufacture, maintenance or operation of helicopters.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  As time passes and mistakes are made, it is hoped that the lessons from these mistakes are taken onboard such tha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t similar mistakes are avoided in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> future.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Looking back over the years since </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">offshore helicopter </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">operation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> commenced, it appears that the safety of such operations has tended to fluctuate in cycles and there is perhaps a fundamental safety lesson to b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e learnt in this respect.  Each operator has to give due attention not only to the safety of their operations but also, of course, to the viability and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">commercial </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">success of each operation.  These two </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">potentially </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">conflicting and inter-related demands are e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">vident throughout all commercial helicopter operations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and a very fine balance between the two has to be maintained if the individual operation is to remain </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">both </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">safe and viable.  From experience, the moment either the commercial side or the safety side be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">comes predominant, then the overall operation tends to suffer.  If there is too much commercial priority</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">being </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">given</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, then the safety side suffers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and co</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rners </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tend to be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> cut </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in order </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to save costs.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This will continue right up until a major incident or acc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ident occurs, whereupon the concentration switches in favour of safety.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Similarly, if too much priority is being given to the safety side the helicopter is continually being serviced or maintained</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, its availability is curtailed,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the commercial flying suff</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ers and income is affected.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Over the years, the cycle of expansion and contraction has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">been evident. The greater danger to the safety of the operations undoubtedly occurs during any major expansion of helicopter operations.  Whenever a new h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">elicopter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> type is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> ordered and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">introduced</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">by an operator, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">there follows the inevitable learning curve as engineers and flight crews gain familiarity and operating experience on the new type.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">From experience it has become inevitable that any new helicopter type intr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oduced is almost guaranteed to suffer from some random and unexpected malfunctions sooner or later.  The sad fact is that helicopters, by their very nature, tend to vibrate more than aeroplanes and, eventually, that vibration builds up until certain parts </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">become affected over time and tend to fracture or break, sometime</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> with catastrophic results.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It is often the case that the individual helicopter type involved in such a catastrophe is operating in more than a single sector of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">North Sea</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and it may be p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ure chance that dictates which state’s helicopter operator suffers the failure when it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">does occur</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Thus it may be questionable to infer that because a particular helicopter type in one sector of the North Sea has suffered a fatal accident, that other sect</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ors operating the same type of helicopter are then deemed to be more safe.  Where mechanical catastrophic failures are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">concerned that relate to the manufacture of a particular helicopter type, then pure chance certainly plays a key role.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Similarly if ther</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e are more of the same types of helicopter ordered, there must be an expansion in the numbers of new pilots and engineers employed to man </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and maintain </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">them and they too must go through a training programme and a learning curve until they become proficient</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> During this time safety incidents do tend to increase. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It is perhaps significant that all three major UK Offshore Helicopter operators are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, I believe,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> currently expanding and seeking more pilots.  In the past, there was a steady flow of ex military pilo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ts to choose from but this source is very limited now and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I do not believe that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">operators are finding it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">all that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">easy to fill their vacancies, especially when potential pilots </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to fund their own training at vast cost.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> As a point of interest, i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">commer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cial </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fixed wing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">aviation generally worldwide</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> it is estimated that by the end of this decade 250,000 new pilots will be required</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> together with 400,000 new engineers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, based solely on the very large numbers of new aircraft currently on order.  The industry s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eems to be slow in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">establishing the necessary criteria for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">meeting these future demands.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Following a total of 5 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> offshore helicopter accidents since February 2009, including two fatal accidents, the industry is currently taking action to review procedur</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">es.  The CAA in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Norway</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, together with EASA, are jointly reviewing offshore operations and the UK Transport Select Committee will also be investigating the issue.  The two fatal accidents were as follows: -</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> April 2009 - Bond Offshore - Eurocopte</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r AS332L2 – </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> – 16 fatalities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">23</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">rd</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> August 2013 - CHC Scotia – Eurocopter AS332L2 – Sumburgh – 4 fatalities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The 2009 accident was caused by a catastrophic failure of the main gearbox which, in turn, caused the main rotor to separate from the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">helicopter.  The 2013 accident appears not to have been attributable to any mechanical malfunction and the helicopter was flown into the sea whilst on approach to Sumburgh airport.  The AAIB Bulletin on this accident appears to point to the possibility tha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t the helicopter was allowed to enter a state of Vortex Ring, a low airspeed and almost vertical high rate of descent where the flow of air through the rotors re-circulates and the rate of descent increases and control is then lost.  Taking these two fatal</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> accidents it would appear that the first was possibly due to a manufacturing and/or maintenance problem whilst the second may have been attributable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> pilots</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  This is of course pure conjecture at this early stage in the investigation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the final A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">AIB report on the accident is now awaited.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Looking now at the overall safety record </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">specifically and only </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sector of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">North Sea helicopter </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oil and gas </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">support operations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> since they started, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as far </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as it is possible to establish and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">if my </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">early </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">records are correct</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> there have been a total of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">16</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> fat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">al accidents with a total of 13</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">9</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> fatalities during the 48 years of operations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">between</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1965 and 2013</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">That equates to approx</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">imately 1 fatal accident every 3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> years and just </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">fewer than</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> fatalities p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">er year</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Whilst the total Norwegian statistics for the whole period are unavailable,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Helikopter Service AS, a Norwegian operator who, in the 12 year period between 1973 and 1985 suffered 5 fatal accidents, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">one in just over every 2 years</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) and 41 fatalities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (an average of 3.42 fatalities per year)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Note</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> When trying to assess the hours flown between</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the period 1965 – 1975, it is assumed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the number of flyin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">g hours during those</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> initial few years</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of operations was fairly limited until gas was discovered and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y hours flown are discounted.  T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">here were no fatal accidents in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> sector before 1976</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The year 2013 is included with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">same hours</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2012</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Reference has been made</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and information obtained</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">North Sea</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> operations </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">outlined in: - </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">CAP 641 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">RHOSS Report Feb 1995</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> with 17 safety recommendations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">CAA - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Offshore Helicopter Safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">D A Howson 14 May 2013 </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Flight International 17</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> September 2013</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It has been difficult to estimate with any precision the total numbers of UK Operator’s hours flown </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in support</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> specifically</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of the offshore industry over the whole period,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as most UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> operators have also been</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> involved in other public transport operations.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Appr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oximate </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">total </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hours flown </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1976 – </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2013 (38 years) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">= 3,546,300 hours</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">At a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n average annual tot</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">al of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">=      93,300 hours</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It may be of interest to note that a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> brief </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">safety </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">comparison </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">was undertaken </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">over a 3 year</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">period </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(1979 – 1981</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> – see below</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) between</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> World Jet Transport operations </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and Offshore H</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">elicopter operations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  This brief comparison sho</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">wed that the offshore flying was </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">relatively </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">safer than the fixed wing worldwide public transport flying</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> during that three year period</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  It would perhaps be of further interest to do a similar comparison for the last five years</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(2009 – 2013</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) where the avera</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ge </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">offshore annual</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">flying </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hours were approximately 74,265 hours. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">During this period there were</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 2 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">x </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fatal accidents and 20 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">x </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fatalities (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1 x</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> fatality per 18,566 hours</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and 1 x fatal accident every 2.5 years)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and this shows a lowering of the offshore safety standards when compared to earlier comparisons. In the following comparison the annual offshore helicopter hours flown are more than double the average totals over the last five years.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">FIXED WING WORLD JET</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> TRANSPORT</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">YEAR   </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">HOURS (,000)  FATALITIES   ACCIDENTS    FATAL ACCIDENTS</span></p><p style="margin:0